Being an introverted creative and valuing one's privacy should not be a contradiction, but it often is. Most online sources and coaches advise working with the (evil) tech giants and behaving extroverted. Advertise here, follow the algorithm, show your personality. Get a blue checkmark from that service, be available around the clock, answer inquiries with a video of yourself, respond immediately. Video, video, video.
1/3
For me, it is a year of changes.
I don't want to feed the tech giants with money, data, and my energy. Or coaches who have their own extroverted solution and try to convince everyone of it. I'm looking for new ways to run a business, while at the same time fighting against my long-held belief that you have to do things a certain way in order to be successful.
Wish me luck!
I have already taken the first steps.
I canceled my FB account, removed all Meta and Pinterest trackers from my website, and deleted my private WhatsApp account.
Yesterday, I also removed Google Analytics, the last external tracker, from my website, and I feel good about that.
Recently, I subscribed to a European CRM to have better GDPR support, and I will be moving my business there in the coming weeks.
I have transferred my MX account to Proton and now have complete SPF, DKIM, and DMARC, without having to pay Google anything for regular email validation.
3/3
